WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Can a helpful, well-meaning tool still be racist?

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:06.880
That's the trap of technological benevolence.

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:13.040
We usually assume that without explicit, hate-filled intent, a new machine is completely neutral.

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:19.440
But take the police throwbot, a throwable surveillance machine designed to keep tactical teams safe.

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:24.960
Pitched purely for public safety, it lets officers survey dangerous real estate with their eyes,

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:29.360
not their bodies. But this do-gooding ethos acts as a moral cover.

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:34.800
It shields the tool from scrutiny as it's dropped into an unjust, deeply unequal system.

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:38.320
Here, marginalized populations are routinely denigrated,

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:41.280
and black victims are already treated as disposable.

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:46.320
So the genuine intent to protect officers ends up expanding surveillance against vulnerable

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:50.960
communities. Because a racist system doesn't need hate-filled programmers,

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:54.960
it just needs detached designers prioritizing benevolent aims,

00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:58.640
while their shiny new tools codify historical neglect.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:03.440
So while that individual throwbot might successfully protect a single tactical officer

00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:07.760
from physical harm during a standoff, that exact same technology ultimately

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:12.960
arms and enforces a fundamentally unequal system of surveillance across the entire city.
